<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-424-830  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 424 830.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  July 10 1989 n546 p50(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The effects of 1992 on European ICs.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Koot, Cees W.M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The establishment of the European Economic Community in 1992 willhave far-reaching economic effects, including a one-off gain of200 billion European currency units, an increase in gross domesticproduct, new jobs and a drop in consumer prices.andP;  A major problemfacing the European integrated-circuit industry as 1992 approachesis the imbalance of trade in EDP goods.andP;  Europe lags far behindthe US and Japan in developing an electronics industry, and isoverly dependent on imported electronics.andP;  A viable IC industry isimportant to a region's development because electronics are anenabling technology for social advancement.andP;  Europe needs tobecome self-supporting to allow research and development.andO;Investment in industrialization, designing new systems withadvanced ICs, and supporting a strong design community will helpbuild an electronics infrastructure.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     European Economic CommunitySemiconductor IndustryEuropeIntegrated CircuitsEconomicsInternational Trade.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>